8a MA(1)Models

set.seed(100) ;
par(mfrow=c(2,1)) 
w<-rnorm(220,0,1)   
v<-filter(w, sides=1, c(.3, 1))[-(1:20)] 
plot.ts(v, main="MA(1)",col="blue",ylab=expression(X[t]),xlab="Time") 
acf(v, main="")

8b AR(1)Models

set.seed(100); # This allows us to reproduce our results
par(mfrow=c(2,1)) #This gives us our graphs in 2 rows, 1 column
w<-rnorm(220,0,1) #noise with 20 extra iterations to avoid startup issues 
y<-filter(w+2, filter=c(.1, .4), method="recursive")[-(1:20)] #AR(1). The c term represents the coefficients and the last term removes the first 20 iterations
plot.ts(y, main="AR(1)",col="blue",ylab=expression(X[t]),xlab="Time") #This plot the MA(1) model
acf(y,main="")

8c Nonconstant Trend

set.seed(100); # This allows us to reproduce our results
par(mfrow=c(2,1)) #This gives us our graphs in 2 rows, 1 column
t=seq(1,200,1); #This gives our iterations starting from t=1 to t=100, with a step size of 1
Mt<-4+3*(t**2); #Linear Trend
Wt<-rnorm(length(t),0,1) #Y_t\sim WN(0,1)
Xt<-Mt+.1*Wt #Time series with linear trend
plot.ts(Xt,type="o",xlab="Time",ylab=expression(X[t]),main="Nonconstant Trend") #This plots the time series with a nonconstant trend
lines(t,Mt,col="red") #This is the graph of linear trend itself
acf(Xt, main="") #This plots the ACF

8d Seasonal trend

set.seed(100);  # This allows us to reproduce our results
par(mfrow=c(2,1)) #This gives us our graphs in 2 rows, 1 column
t=seq(1,200,1) #This gives our iterations starting from t=1 to t=200, with a step size of 1
St<- 6*cos(pi*t/3) #Periodic Trend
Wt<-rnorm(length(t),0,1) #White Noise
Zt<-St+Wt #Time series with seasonal component
plot(t,Zt,xlab="Time",ylab=expression(X[t]), main="Seasonal Trend") #This plots our data points
lines(t,St,col="red")
acf(Zt, main="")
